# Fraud Detection Updates Implementation Walkthrough

The updated fraud detection logic has been implemented. This system continuously monitors all transactions and immediately blocks any transaction that meets one of several newly established criteria, protecting user funds and ensuring regulatory compliance.

## Changes Made

- **Transaction Service Updates (`TransactionService.java`)**:
  - Replaced simple amount-based checking with a comprehensive `checkFraud` validation method.
  - Added real-time checking for the **24-hour transaction limit**. Any attempt to transact a total of more than ₹100,000 in a 24-hour window across all transaction types will be flagged.
  - Added real-time checking for **High-Frequency Transactions**. Any attempt to make more than 5 transactions within a rolling 10-minute window will be flagged as suspicious behavior.
  - Implemented **Target Account KYC Checking**. When depositing or transferring to another account, the target account's owner is cross-verified against the `user-service`. If the KYC status is absent or not `APPROVED`, the transaction is blocked.

- **Data Access & DTOs**:
  - Updated `TransactionRepository.java` to support querying recent user transactions by timestamp and user ID.
  - Introduced the `UserClient` and `UserProfileResponse` DTO to the `transaction-service` in order to communicate with `user-service` to check KYC statuses.
  - Added a `fraudReason` field to the `TransactionEvent` schema, enabling downstream systems to know exactly *why* a transaction was blocked.

- **Notification Service (`NotificationConsumer.java`)**:
  - Updated the Kafka consumer to interpret the incoming `fraudReason` and format the email/SMS/in-app alert message explicitly with the reason, improving transparency to the end user.

## What was verified
- Feign client injection (`UserClient`) and appropriate HTTP paths.
- Kafka schema parity between publisher (transaction service) and consumer (notification service).
- Java time API usage correctly implementing rolling windows (10 minutes, 24 hours).
- Total amount cumulative reduction mapping for limits.

## Validation Results
- The codebase correctly incorporates all rules requested, falling back to clean transaction flows if none of the risk scenarios are breached.

> [!TIP]
> The thresholds (5 transactions/10min and ₹100,000/24hr) are currently hardcoded constants in the logic. In future iterations, they can be parameterized via application properties or an administrative dashboard for real-time adjusting.
